x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Over the years, we =
talked to Fox=E2=80=99s leadership, and they believe strongly in skinnier b=
undles. Their view is that it makes no sense to launch a virtual channel pa=
ckage at 85 channels for $85. What Fox is playing for is that at some point=
 there=E2=80=99ll be a logical virtual player. Maybe it=E2=80=99s YouTube T=
V in three to five years if they say, <i>Look, all our viewing data shows t=
he same thing</i>, which is that viewers only want to watch the broadcast n=
ets, the sports-backed assets, a little news once in a while, and that=E2=
=80=99s it. What Fox is holding out for is the second or third iteration of=
 these virtual bundles that become skinnier because they don=E2=80=99t want=
 to go <i>=C3=A0 la carte</i> and create a Fox Sports app or Fox News app. =
<br/><br/>They=E2=80=99re benefiting from their strategy. They=E2=80=99re b=
efuddled that these distributors haven=E2=80=99t changed the model very
much. All the survey work we=E2=80=99ve done has found that 50 channels for=
 $50 is the sticky point. <br/><br/>We had<b> John Malone</b> speak a coupl=
e months ago, and he had this notion of: <i>There=E2=80=99s live and then t=
here=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Crandom access=E2=80=9D</i>=E2=80=94a phrase he used=
=2E You need a live bundle and then thi=
s random-access layer where people cho=
ose what they want away from live. And if I=E2=80=99m Fox, that seems like =
a logical place to go. Maybe before you blow yourself up and go over the to=
p=E2=80=94everyone but Disney is losing money=E2=80=94you hope that someone=
 shows up with a more rational video bundle.<br/></td>
